But this demon, it treated her like a walking portable grill, following her everywhere she went, cooking its meals right on her body. The girl, however, couldn't see the demon at all, leaving her best friend, who actually could, terrified out of her mind. Desperate, the friend decided to take her to a sacred temple, hoping the gods could help drive the demon away. But the demon shamelessly followed them, marching straight into the temple without a care in the world. the friend threw a single coin into the offering box and made a wish. The moment the wish was made, two deities suddenly appeared behind the demon. They began chanting a powerful incantation, and in one swift move, they snapped the demon's arms and slammed it to the ground. The friend finally started to breathe a sigh of relief, but then the demon went completely berserk. As the deities prepared to strike again, the demon broke free, crushed their arms and devoured them whole. The friend stared in pure horror at the rampaging demon, while the girl, still totally oblivious, thought her friend was admiring the sunset. She smiled and pulled her friend in for a selfie. But right behind them, An enormous deity appeared five times the size of the demon. Gripping it tightly by the head, the girl kept posing happily, completely unaware. Her friend glanced at the photo they just took, and when she saw the terrifying figure in the frame, she froze in fear. Then she noticed the two deities that had been eaten slowly standing back up. Only then did she realize they were merely attendants of a far greater god. At that very moment, as the attendants spoke with their master, one of them turned and looked directly at the friend. Faced with such a horrifying divine presence, the friend's entire body went cold with dread. And then the great god leaned down close to her ear and whispered.

voice_to_text: The next day, the man's head was still tilted down. He had never seen the other person's face, even when they were in the same place. One day, the man sat in a cafe waiting for his medical test results. He noticed couples everywhere around him. At that moment, his heart felt empty. He longed for a love of his own. When the diagnosis appeared in front of him, he saw a triangle on the scan. His heart tightened. His neck would never return to normal. At that moment, he remembered that people tilt their head slightly when they kiss. So he stole a billboard of a beautiful woman by the pool wearing his best suit. He leaned in to kiss her photo, but no matter how hard he tried, he could never reach her lips. He ended up tearing the head off the billboard. It was then that he heard a bird singing outside. He leaned to look and by chance, he saw a woman for the first time. Their eyes met. In that moment, they both thought, maybe this is the person I was meant to find. He rushed home to put on his best jacket. She fixed her hair. Both of them dreamed of this first meeting. But tragically, because of their bodies and heights, they walked in circles for a long time without seeing each other. Discouraged, they drifted apart. One went upstairs, the other went downstairs, as if fate was playing another cruel trick yet The moment they crossed paths, the little bird sang again. They both turned around. Finally, their eyes aligned perfectly, and love began to bloom. The woman's head naturally tilted up.

voice_to_text: I wanted to test my boyfriend's loyalty, so I locked myself in a secret room to fake my disappearance. He just got home from work. I watched his every reaction through the one way mirror. He quickly found the goodbye letter I left. Instantly panicked, he searched every corner of the house frantically. Then he tried calling my phone but no one answered. Seeing his eyes turn red, I felt a little thrill inside. He still love me after all. But his sadness quickly turned to anger. He threw the flowers he bought for me held against the mirror. I jumped back in shock. This game was getting out of hand. I searched for the key, planning to surprise him. But after looking everywhere, I suddenly remembered I'd been in such a rush, the only key to the secret room was left outside. This was bad. I rushed to the mirror and pounded for help, but the soundproofing was too good. He couldn't hear a thing. My cries for help were useless. I tried calling out but there was no signal in here. Desperate now, I grabbed a chair and smashed it against the glass. The mirror didn't even crack. I was finally paying for what I done, completely trapped in this secret room. This wasn't just any secret room. The old landlady had told me her late husband built it to hide from enemies. The walls were reinforced with metal, two windows made of one way bulletproof glass. I. Could see everything in the bedroom and bathroom. Speakers only worked one way to hear outside. After telling me that she left for Germany, now nobody knew I was locked in here. That night he came home after searching for me. I was right in front of him, but he couldn't see me. Watching him break down crying, my heart was being torn apart. He reported me missing to the police, but they told him to wait at home. They'd investigate slowly. Meanwhile, I was in the secret room, chipping at the walls day after day. When. When hungry, I ate expired canned food. When thirsty, I drank stale water. Days later, he watched the video I'd left and said with contempt, good luck to you. I exploded with rage. He was giving up on me already. Watching him walk to the bathroom, I kicked the water pipes in fury. The sink actually rippled. Maybe there was hope. I grabbed a steel pipe and kept banging. The ripples were clearly visible. But with the thunderstorm outside, he just stared at himself in the mirror until he turned and walked away. Another chance for rescue had vanished.

voice_to_text: The man stretched his arm out of the train window and seven minutes later, his arm froze into an ice sculpture. The man in the suit tapped it lightly, producing a crisp sound, then grabbed a large iron hammer, swung it and smashed it down. The people below dared not make a sound. After all, he had only thrown a shoe at a wealthy person, yet faced such harsh punishment in the future. To fight the worsening greenhouse effect, countries launched a freezing machine code named CW seven, designed to lower global temperatures to a controllable range. But it triggered a series of chain reactions, plunging earth into an ice age. Most people froze to death, while the survivors took refuge on a massive, perpetually moving train that circled the globe. It had been running for 17 years. Inside, people were divided into classes. The wealthy road at the front, eating steak and partying daily. The middle class served as enforcers and soldiers in the middle cars. And the poor, who had no ticket but snuck on, were brutally controlled in the rear cars. The space was cramped, the air thick with body odor, sweat and decay. They ate blackish protein blocks every day. To make matters worse, the front would send people to kidnap children, and any resistance was met with torture, like the man who had thrown the shoe. This constant oppression LED to rebellion among the poor in the rear cars, and Chris became their leader for Years they collected iron barrels, waiting for the right moment to break through the front gates. Everything was ready. They just needed the right opportunity. One day, while everyone was lining up for food, three electric gates at the front unexpectedly opened simultaneously. Chris knew the time had come. He dropped his protein block, rushed through the crowd and grabbed a soldier's gun. But it was empty. The bullets had been used up four years ago during a suppressed uprising. Chris had gambled, correctly. Receiving the signal, the others lifted iron barrels, pushing them forward to block the carriage door. Chris LED the charge, fighting hand to hand with the soldiers. The crowd surged forward, quickly overwhelming the front line. But the soldiers were tough opponents and one large bald soldier swung a massive iron block back and forth. The rebels couldn't handle him. Then a young man took off his jacket, accelerated, leapt onto the bald soldier and drove a knife into his heart. They also obtained the prison keys. Chris's next plan was to rescue Jillian, the safety expert, from the train prison. Jillian knew how to open the electric train doors. The prison consisted of cabinet like cells and as expected, Jillian was inside, but he wouldn't help for free. His daughter had to come along and opening each door cost 2 Kronos. Jillian's daughter Yuna had a special skill. Her ears were so sharp she could hear how many people were behind each door using her Ability. They opened the first prison door. This carriage had once housed soldiers but was now empty. For the first time in 17 years, the oppressed rear car passengers saw the outside world. Sunlight touched their faces and the world outside looked just like before they boarded, still covered in ice and snow, they moved to the next carriage where protein blocks were mass produced. Despite eating these blocks for 17 years, no one knew what they were made of. Climbing to the top of the machinery, Chris was shocked when he saw the raw materials.

They looked outside and realized a horrific car crash had just happened right in front of their house. Having just moved into their new home, the two were totally creeped out, thinking they'd gotten the worst luck. Little did they know this was only the beginning. The next day, Teddy checked the news, found out the guy who died the night before was a young football player. There was a hidden curve right by their driveway, and he couldn't hit the brakes in time, which cost him his life. Teddy felt really bad for the guy, but since the crash happened right outside his house, he figured he had a responsibility to do something about it. So, so he took a close look at that curve and noticed tons of old, worn skid marks on the pavement. Clearly, this wasn't the first accident there. To keep another tragedy from happening, Teddy used the lawn mower to clear out all the weeds along the road, making the hidden warning sign much more visible. Every night when he had nothing to do, he'd sit in the yard and keep a close eye on the road. But even that wasn't enough to stop another accident. One day, Teddy was grilling in the backyard when he heard a loud crash. He ran over and saw another car had been in a terrible Wreck, the driver, still had a pulse, but Teddy had no clue how to perform first aid. By the time the police and ambulance arrived, the driver had already passed away. Eddie was consumed with guilt, blaming himself for not knowing any first aid skills, for letting the guy die right in front of him. He poured out his heartache to Brooke, saying if he'd been able to give the driver CPR right away, maybe he would have survived. But Brooke couldn't handle it anymore. She insisted they had to move out within a week. With accidents happening one after another, she thought the house was cursed. No wonder the previous owner had sold it at an absurdly low price. On top of that, their son kept saying he could smell a rotten stench in the house. Brooke was convinced it meant way too many tragedies had happened there and kids could pick up on that bloody stench. But Teddy refused to move. He was dead set on staying, determined to put an end to the tragedies once and for all.

voice_to_text: One senior who ditched natural grass to make life easier is now seeing red courtesy of the city. It may look real, but this is synthetic grass, and it's LED to a turf war with City Hall. Homeowner Frank Leoni installed the fake grass on his New York lawn because he's in his 80s, he's had a stroke and has limited mobility. Shortly after the turf went in, a complaint was filed by a neighbor. Frank got a notice from the city, receiving help from former Councilor Karen Stints. Leone called a bylaw officer to inspect the lawn, getting approval last October, and he got it in writing. Leone thought it was over, but just a month later, a building inspector from the city said the lawn is not permeable, meaning water can't pass through it, and he's being charged for failure to comply with an order. This despite the approval of a bylaw officer. He's now being served with additional notices of violation, including fines, if he doesn't replace his grass within the next 30 days. According to Leone, he was told that the primary issue was a lack of water flow, even though his turf has many holes and it allows water to flow through easily. And they can solve it for Frank, and they can solve it across the city. She says that the bylaws should be amended to include synthetic turf so that a mix up like this doesn't happen again.

But coincidentally, the company was having a meeting today. Homer panicked. At that moment, Cletus suggested that Homer should buy balloons to give to the leaders. Homer Learned that hydrogen was discovered by Cletus by accident when he was chopping firewood in the yard. He goes back to the office with the balloons. Burns can tell at a glance that they're pure helium. It turns out that the nuclear power plant spends a lot of money every year to buy helium. Homer tells Burns where they come from. Burns names Homer the best employee. He then goes to take Smith to trick Cletus. But Cletus pulls out his own wine and says he'll drink before he talks business. Burns drink and instantly feels happy. He then wakes up in his office in order to have cheap helium to use. He tells Homer to befriend Cletus. He then tricks Cletus into signing a contract. Homer wants to say no, but then he talks to thugs. Homer puts on some suspenders and befriends Cletus. Then he did something that made Cletus trust him, so he took Homer up on his offer to use pigs instead of human labor after a profound exchange of ideas. CLE it's really considered Homer a friend. He put Homer to the test with his homebrew. Burns sensed that the time was right. He took out a contract and asked Homer to trick Cletus into signing it. Cletus he plucked a chicken feather and stuck resin on it and was ready to sign the contract. At a critical moment, Homer had a moment of conscience and stopped Cletus. Then he told Cletus the truth. But Cletus forgave Homer when he Learned about it. Suddenly Burns showed up with his thugs. Eventually, Cletus resolved the crisis by a wide margin.

voice_to_text: The boy actually started having bad thoughts about his family's nanny, but the nanny didn't get angry. Instead, she thought the boy was very childish. However, the boy didn't give up. He kept looking for a chance to make a move. That day, his parents suddenly had to go out at home. Only he and the nanny, Annie, were left. Seeing this, the boy immediately locked the door. Then he set up a romantic candlelight dinner, invited Annie to eat while watching a movie. In the end, he even deliberately switched the channel to a horror movie because he read online that watching horror movies with a girl will release dopamine. Sure enough, Annie got scared and held his hand. He took the chance to lean closer to her and boldly reached out his hand unexpectedly. Annie didn't fall for it. Before she could react, the boy suddenly leaned in and forcibly kissed her. This bold move was condemned by Annie. Right after that, something strange happened. The Santa Claus that was placed outside the door suddenly appeared by the window, and the door that was just locked was now opened. Annie thought a bad guy had broken in. She immediately chose to call the police, but the boy, in order to stop her, actually threw the phone into the fish tank. Before Annie could pick up the phone, suddenly there was a knock on the door. When they opened it, it turned out to be the boy's friend trying To scare them on purpose. Just as he let out a sigh of relief, the sound of breaking glass came again from upstairs. They carefully went to the second floor to check. They found a brick on the ground. On it was written, must die tonight. Then a beam of white light shone in from the window. It scared the friend so much, he ran away immediately. Annie quickly took the boy and hid in the closet. At this moment, a masked intruder broke in with a gun. Annie held the boy tightly, not daring to make a sound. But suddenly she realized the mask the intruder wore was exactly the same as the boys. Only then did she understand that all of this was directed and staged by the boy himself.

voice_to_text: She cheated on me with 6 different guys while we were dating each other. So if I were you, bro, I would be careful. He raised an eyebrow and explained that he was only there to get free food and to try to make me jealous enough to give her another chance. It was the stupidest thing I had heard. I looked over at my ex's face was super red with embarrassment and realized that it was actually true. I felt a serious rush of ego boost, but at the same time, I felt something unexpected too. Like, dude, call me stupid. But I felt pretty touched that she would go this far just to try to win me back. It definitely wasn't the best way to win me back, but definitely creative. So I told her jokingly that if she really wanted me back, she should try showing up here alone for another month to prove that she really meant it. I walked off to finish the rest of my shift. After that, she really did show up every day with a book or journal sitting at the same booth waiting for my shift to finish. I didn't even really talk to her much and she still came around. Weeks went by and on the last day of the month, she walked into Waffle House with a huge smile on her face. I walked over with her usual order and sat beside her in the booth. She asked me, If I would finally be her boyfriend again. I smiled back and said, absolutely not. I reminded her that she cheated on me with several guys and one of them was my best friend. She picked up the glass of water and thought about splashing it all over me. Instead, she splashed water on her own face to wake herself up and left, angrily ripping up one of the menus in the restaurant out of frustration before walking out the front door. The entire angry scene was crazy cute, like, ah, there goes my little Harley Quinn. I grinned and told my manager that I was finally quitting. I chased after her and apologized, saying that I wanted to get back at her a little for the horrible mess she put me through before I unzipped my jacket and wrapped it around her head to help her stay warm. After seeing water still drip down from her hair, I took her home that night and we talked about setting new boundaries if we wanted the relationship to work better this time. To this day, we're still together and no longer the toxic kids we used to be. Also for our prenup, we had a fun photo shoot at that same Waffle House, forever reminding us of our ridiculous and petty days.

voice_to_text: What's the pettiest thing someone has done to you? I work at a Waffle House as one of the cooks and my ex girlfriend likes to come around and set up each of her dates there only when she knows I'm working. It had been four months since our breakup, so I didn't really understand why she would waste effort coming around and showing off that she could easily land a guy. It really bothered me at first watching her laugh and enjoy each date just like how we used to. I even thought about burning their food or putting something weird in. I settled for making their food extra salty for fun. After seeing the 3rd and 4th guy, I got used to it and just treated them like another customer with no connection to me. Eventually, my ex girlfriend settled with a guy I like to call Beanie based on the black and green beanie had he liked to wear on every date. They visit Waffle House about twice a week after class. I wasn't really suspicious about their relationship or anything until I was given a different shift. They ended up changing their meal time to match my schedule. That's when I started to really think about why they kept coming around and why they needed to go out on a date while I was there at work. Like, was I really that great of a chef here? So during my break one time, I decided to Walk over and ask them why they kept coming around to have a date specifically. While I was on the clock, my ex girlfriend sipped on her Sprite and asked, what do you mean? Are you saying we're doing this on purpose? I nodded and said, yeah, that's exactly what I was implying. She sighed and leaned back in her seat, crossing her arms before looking up at me and asking, are you just jealous? I sighed, feeling like I wasted my time and said, why would I be jealous when I'm the one who broke up with you in the first place? Her mouth flung open to argue back, but I tired my attention to Beanie and said.

voice_to_text: At noon, the doorbell rang and mom flew to answer feverishly. An exhausted woman stood there clutching her purse, thanking mom over and over for babysitting. Behind her, a girl about 11 with dark hair hung back, clearly uneasy. Take all the time you need, mom purred in a voice I'd never heard before. The second their car turned the corner, something in Mom's face shifted into pure predator. She grabbed the girl's wrist hard enough to leave marks and dragged her toward Daniela's room. Welcome home, baby. The girl's confusion turned to fear. My name is not Daniela. It's Katie, she, I whispered. The sound of Mom's palm hitting her face made me flinch. You are Daniela, Mom shrieked. Everything accelerated into a nightmare. Mom commanded Katie to undress, but when she shook her head, mom grabbed the Scissors from Daniela's desk. Katie tried to bolt, but mom caught her by the hair. I watched frozen in horror as she cut through Katie's clothes with violent precision, humming Daniela's lullaby. Katie stood there exposed and sobbing while mom forced Daniela's tiny dress over her head. Bathroom became a torture chamber. Mom dragged the screaming girl in while I watched in horror. Through the mirror, I watched mom slather bleach on her hair. I want my mommy, she wailed. I am your mommy. Mom, god gave you back to me. In one desperate moment, when mom turned for more dye, Katie scooped bleach and smeared it across Mom's eyes. Mom's Scream was inhuman as she clawed at her face. Katie sprinted out and yelled for help. I flew downstairs and dove into the pantry with my phone. I whispered frantically to 9, 1, 1 while Katie sobs mixed with Mom's rage above us. Those minutes waiting for sirens felt like hours. When they finally broke down Daniela's door, they found mom sitting calmly on the bed, brushing both Katie's hair and the dolls. My two danielas have finally met, she announced it's proudly. Katie threw herself at the officers while mom fought like a wild animal, screaming, don't take my babies again, even as they wrestled her into handcuffs. The little girl's mom placed a restraining order on our family and Mom's been institutionalized 8 months now. Last time I visited, she grabbed my hand and whispered, I forgive you for sending Daniela away again. She smiled and for a moment I thought I saw a glimpse of mom I had before the crash until she mentioned another patient had Daniela's exact laugh. After that, dad and I cleaned out Daniela's room together and donated everything, including that horrible doll.

voice_to_text: Wasn't seventeen. She was only fifteen. And her mother wasn't just stealing insulin money. The woman had been using Sarah to pay for drugs. The pharmacy cashier later told me Sarah came in with different men every week, always looking terrified. Mrs. Putin pulled me aside and whispered, this girl has been through hell. Are you sure you can handle this? I looked at Sarah sitting on my couch, still clutching that old backpack with everything she owned, and knew I couldn't abandon her. The custody process took six. Once Sarah's mother contested it, not because she wanted her daughter back, but because losing custody meant losing her income source. I had to hire a lawyer I couldn't afford and take time off work I desperately needed. During the court hearings, more truth came out. Sarah had been supporting herself since age 12. She he'd Learned to forge her mother's signature, manage her own medical care, and even had a secret job cleaning offices at night just to afford insulin. The judge was horrified. Sarah's mother got five years for child endangerment. I got temporary custody, then permanent guardianship when Sarah turned 16. My ex had started telling people I was probably a predator for taking in a teenage girl. School was another battle. Sarah tested three grade levels behind in everything except math and science. The guidance counselor wanted to put her in remedial classes, but I saw how brilliant she was. I hired tutors with money I didn't Have and sat with her every night until 2:00am studying. The breakthrough came junior year when Sarah aced the state chemistry exam. Suddenly, colleges were calling. Harvard, Stanford, Johns Hopkins. They all wanted her. But Sarah almost didn't apply anywhere. She was convinced she didn't deserve it, that someone like her couldn't become a doctor. I had to literally drive her to the guidance office and watch her submit applications. Medical school was worse. Sarah called me at least twice a week, having panic attacks, convinced she didn't belong. Other students came from doctor families with connections. Sarah came from nothing. That was eight years ago. Sarah graduated valedictorian, got a full scholarship to medical school and just finished her residency. She's now an endocrinologist helping other diabetic kid.

voice_to_text: What made you call the police on your own mother? My seven year old sister Daniela was singing in the back seat behind me when a truck ran the red light and slammed into us at top speed. By the time the car stopped flipping, Daniela became permanently silent. After hours trying to save her, the doctors told us she was gone. Mom climbed into the hospital bed and pulled Daniela against her chest, rocking her for three hours. Mommy's here, baby. Dad just stood frozen when the nurses pried my sister from Mom's arms. And while they fought, I threw up, knowing I survived and Daniela didn't. The first few weeks blurred together with mom crying in Danielle's room for hours. Dad would hold her shoulders and whisper that everything would be okay. I kept making her chamomile tea, but the cups always went cold on the nightstand. She couldn't stop staring at Danielle things long enough to drink them. Our grief therapist said this was normal and everyone processes loss differently. So we didn't worry when mom started making Daniela's bed every morning. Or arrange the stuffed animals in perfect rows, just how Daniela liked them. We thought maybe this ritual was helping her cope with the loss. The day Daniela would have turned 9, mom showed up with a wrapped birthday present, saying she'd already bought it before the accident. An obvious lie, but dad and I let it slide because what harm could one gift do To an already broken family. A month later, mom walked through the door carrying a life size doll that looked exactly like Daniela, with real human hair and her exact shade. She sat me down to show how she could brush his hair, just like Daniela's bedtime routine. I forced myself to nod, my heart breaking from the desperate sight. The next few days spiraled out of control. Mom dressed the doll in new outfits every morning and took it everywhere in Daniela's wagon. She did both voices like the doll could actually respond. People at the mall grabbed their children and hurried away from us. Dad found the three thousand dollar credit card charge. When he confronted her, she clutched the doll, screaming, you can't put a price on our daughter! He started sleeping on the couch that night. Things got worse when she pulled me out of school claiming it was too dangerous. She set up homeschooling with three play settings at our kitchen table. Week after week, I sat there watching her teach that doll alongside me. Until one morning I couldn't take it anymore. One morning I finally snapped and said, stop it! Daniela is gone! Mom sobbed. You abandoned her in that car and now you're doing it again! The guilt hit me so hard I couldn't breathe. I'm here too, I mumbled, while she cradled that doll like a real child, while tears streamed down her face. Two weeks after dad left, mom started Acting strange, she'd leave the doll behind and disappear, returning with stories about her wonderful new friend and the woman's precious daughter. I found her phone with Daniela's photo replaced by a stranger's child. She has Daniela's exact laugh, mom said. Behind me, her eyes.

video_description: Jubal in the morning radio programâ€Brooke and jubalâ€#trending #fyp #dateupdate #brookeandjubal #phonecall
voice_to_text: At noon, the doorbell rang and mom flew to answer feverishly. An exhausted woman stood there clutching her purse, thanking mom over and over for babysitting. Behind her, a girl about 11 with dark hair hung back, clearly uneasy. Take all the time you need, mom purred in a voice I'd never heard before. The second their car turned the corner, something in Mom's face shifted into pure predator. She grabbed the girl's wrist hard enough to leave marks and dragged her toward Daniela's room. Welcome home, baby. The girl's confusion turned to fear. My name is not Daniela. It's Katie, she, I whispered. The sound of Mom's palm hitting her face made me flinch. You are Daniela, Mom shrieked. Everything accelerated into a nightmare. Mom commanded Katie to undress, but when she shook her head, mom grabbed the Scissors from Daniela's desk. Katie tried to bolt, but mom caught her by the hair. I watched frozen in horror as she cut through Katie's clothes with violent precision, humming Daniela's lullaby. Katie stood there exposed and sobbing while mom forced Daniela's tiny dress over her head. Bathroom became a torture chamber. Mom dragged the screaming girl in while I watched in horror. Through the mirror, I watched mom slather bleach on her hair. I want my mommy, she wailed. I am your mommy. Mom, god gave you back to me. In one desperate moment, when mom turned for more dye, Katie scooped bleach and smeared it across Mom's eyes. Mom's Scream was inhuman. As she clawed at her face, Katie sprinted out and yelled for help. I flew downstairs and dove into the pantry with my phone. I whispered frantically to 9, 1, 1 while Katie sobs mixed with Mom's rage above us. Those minutes waiting for sirens felt like hours. When they finally broke down Daniela's door, they found mom sitting calmly on the bed, brushing both Katie's hair and the dolls. My two danielas have finally met, she announced proudly. Katie threw herself at the officers while mom fought like a wild animal, screaming, don't take my babies again, even as they wrestled her into handcuffs. The little girl's mom placed a restraining order on our family and Mom's been institutionalized 8 months now. Last time I visited, she grabbed my hand and whispered, I forgive you for sending Daniela away again. She smiled and for a moment I thought I saw a glimpse of mom I had before the crash until she mentioned another patient had Daniela's exact laugh. After that, dad and I cleaned out Daniela's room together and donated everything, including that horrible doll.

voice_to_text: When a major data breach hit the news, our solution saved a Fortune 500 company from collapse. At 26, I launched my own data security firm. We specialized in agricultural technology. Protecting farm equipment from hackers, securing crop data. I never told my team why I focused on that sector. Last month, my company went public. Three days later, a Facebook message arrived from my mother. We're so proud of you, it said. As if the last eight years hadn't happened. A week later, a certified letter came from a lawyer in Nebraska. My parents farm was $340,000 in debt. Equipment loans, bad harvests, medical bills from Dad's back surgery. The bank was foreclosing in 30 days. The letter ended with my father's cell number. I stared at that number for hours before calling. His voice sounded older. Smaller somehow. Son, he said. Like he'd never thrown me away. We made mistakes. We met at a steakhouse near their farm. Mom hugged me too tight. Dad's hands had new calluses, his face more lines. They avoided mentioning money for the first hour. Finally, dad cleared his throat. The farm's been in our family since your great grandfather. We can't lose it. He slid a folder across the table. Loan statements, foreclosure notices. We're not asking for a handout. Maybe you could be a partner. Looked at these strangers wearing my parents faces. The same people who told me I was dead to them for wanting an education. I took out My phone made a transfer, then showed them the screen. Enough to clear their debt and modernize the equipment. This isn't a partnership, I said. It's a business transaction. The farm now belongs to my company's agricultural division. You can stay on as managers with salary and benefits, or you can leave. Your choice. Mom started crying. Dad's face flushed red. You'd make your own parents employees? You made me an orphan for wanting a future, I replied. Consider this mercy. I stood to leave and paused. That scholarship you tore up? I'm funding ten of them each year for rural kids who want to study technology. I'm naming it after Mrs. Hernandez, not you. They've left six voicemails since then. I've listened to each one, but haven't called back. Some bridges can't be rebuilt once they're burned.

voice_to_text: A woman discovered that her deceased husband seemed to have deceived her for 50 years because she found a videotape he had left behind. After watching its contents, she was utterly shocked. The video showed a girl being brutally murdered, and the entire process seemed very real, not like a movie. The woman couldn't understand why her honest husband would have such a thing. To uncover the truth, the woman hired a detective named Jack at a high price. Jack also watched the videotape. In complete shock, he suggested that the woman turn the tape over to the police for investigation. But Anna immediately rejected this suggestion because she belonged to the most famous family in the area and doing so would inevitably affect the family's reputation. The woman told Jack that she only wanted to know if the video was related to her husband. She promised to pay Jack a fee of $1 million once the investigation was completed. Jack, for the money, unhesitatingly accepted the task, not knowing that this decision would make him regret it for the rest of his life. Jack thought the case was simple, because as long as he could find out the girl's identity, he would know the ins and outs of the matter. Little did he know that a secret buried for many years was about to surface. After returning home, Jack copied the video from the tape to his computer, intending to search for useful clues in the video. Fortunately, Jack did. Find a clue. He discovered that the video was shot 20 years ago. After a month long search, Jack finally found information about the girl among the missing persons. The girl's name was Anna, and she had disappeared 20 years ago at the age of 16. This meant that Anna was indeed murdered in the videotape. To find out the truth, Jack visited Anna's mother's home. Jack immediately asked what had happened before the girl's disappearance, and the mother said that she had a poor relationship with her daughter. After an argument, Anna had run away from home. However, strangely enough, Anna had left without taking any clothes, which it was completely unlike a runaway situation. So Jack searched Anna's room for clues but found nothing. Just as Jack was about to leave, he discovered a diary in the toilet tank. Upon opening it, he found a letter written to Anna's mother inside. The appearance of this letter plunged the entire case into an even greater whirlpool.

voice_to_text: This man found a box in a trash can, but when he opened it, he discovered it was full of sunglasses. This left the man deeply disappointed. So he took one pair and threw the box back into the trash, never knowing that this action would change his life forever. When the man put on the sunglasses, he witnessed a bizarre scene. He saw that a man in a suit had transformed into a monster. But when he removed the sunglasses, the person appeared normal again. The man found this incredible, so he quickly put the sunglasses back on and looked around. Jack was horrified to discover that the entire world had become black and white. Building billboards had turned into strange slogans. Even money had become papers with written messages. And all the books in the bookstore had transformed this way, too. Jack randomly picked up a book to examine it and found that it contained only brainwashing text. As soon as he removed the glasses, everything returned to normal. This discovery left Jack utterly shocked. The man wandered aimlessly through the streets and Jack soon discovered more monsters. Strangely, not everyone turned into monsters. The monsters were all well dressed, upper class people. At this moment, Jack suddenly noticed that the president on television was also a monster. He instantly realized that the country had been taken over by monsters. Just then, a woman wearing a fur coat bumped into Jack and he discovered that she, too, was A monster. Jack immediately began cursing at the woman. The woman was utterly shocked after hearing this. She hadn't expected that Jack had seen through her true identity. The monster immediately used her watch to call other companions. Next second, all the monsters in the supermarket began walking toward them, speaking strange words continuously. Jack instantly realized the danger and quickly ran out of the supermarket before the monsters could attack. Little did he know his behavior had already attracted the attention of all the monsters. Soon, a police officer stopped Jack through his sunglasses. He was horrified to discover that the police officer was also a monster.

voice_to_text: To keep my handsome boyfriend, I faked pregnancy to hide the belly fat. After finishing the disguise, I opened the door. The moment he entered, he gently touched baby and reminded me about today's ultrasound. I broke into a cold sweat. If he found out it was just fat, everything would be ruined. Thankfully, I'm quick witted. I pretended to have morning sickness and rushed into the storage room, pulled a toy doll from my treasure box and stuffed it into the fake belly. This doll was battery powered, perfect for the hospital visit. The unsuspecting doctor was nearly scared to death by the monster laughter on the screen. My boyfriend fainted instantly. Even the experienced doctor lasted less than two seconds before passing out. I punched my belly a few times trying to stop the doll's noise and movement, but accidentally gave birth to it, knocking out my boyfriend again. Terrified, I picked up the doll to check batteries had died. At least the doll's mission was complete. As I tried dragging my boyfriend home, a proposal ring fell from his pocket. Overjoyed, I bent to grab it, but my fat burst the fake belly. Luckily, he was still unconscious. With immense effort, I dragged him home. Just as I relaxed, I remembered my waist fat. If he saw it, he might break up with me. My clever brain, I hatched a new plan. I melted gummy bears in a pot, using the jelly to repair the silicone belly. I scooped the sticky glue and patched the hole. But before I could celebrate, my fat bulged out again. In desperation, I tried stitching it with toothpicks, but underestimated my fat strength. The fake belly burst, shooting toothpicks. That woke my boyfriend. Panicked. I searched for solutions and found when I wrapped super cling film as around a frying pan and strapped it to my stomach. My boyfriend followed the strange sounds and was shocked to see my belly had changed shape. He tapped it suspiciously. It made a metallic sound. Lifting my shirt, I found the pan. Now the fake pregnancy and belly were exposed. I thought he'd leave, but instead he was fascinated by my fat belly. Its jiggly texture mesmerized him. Then he took out the ring and proposed. I didn't fully understand, but felt he must love my chubby belly.

voice_to_text: My husband hung me up and forced me to exercise to collect my fat. I ended up losing 200 pounds because of it. He tasted my sweat and seemed very pleased. Then he put the fat into a machine, instantly turning it into bars of soap. When he washed with this soap, his skin became fair and smooth. My god! It was miraculous! What they didn't notice? A pig's tail had grown on his behind. Oh no! Was it because I ate pork? My husband started developing pig like traits. He then sold this magical soap to a mysterious wealthy man, who happily paid him $10,000 and placed an order for 10 more boxes. My husband agreed delightedly, but I was already skin and bones. I begged him to let me eat the delicious food from the fridge, but he refused outright. Instead, he gave me rotten fruit. Good grief! The smell alone nearly made me vomit last night's dinner. What's more, the soap made from my fat in that state turned black and smelled awful. When he washed with it, boys immediately broke out on his hands. Terrified, he threw the soap away. Just then, the wealthy client called. The delivery deadline was approaching, so he finally unlocked the fridge. My mouth watered at the sight of all the delicious food. But then my husband shoved a whole lobster into my mouth, almost choking me. Next, they forced fed me small fish, making me eat upside down. Soon I Began sweating colorful sweat. My husband used it to make soap. And the soap turned out colorful too. He delivered a box of pink soap to the client. The wealthy man tried a piece and suddenly grew a lobster tail with his hands turning into giant claws. Seeing the client's monstrous transformation, my husband was scared out of his wits. I seized the moment and smeared colorful soap on his head, too. The next second, he grew the head of a bull. Now he can no longer oppress or exploit me.

voice_to_text: This filthy homeless woman actually had golden feet. Even her toenails were pure gold. I nearly lost my mind with excitement. Just then, a fly flew straight into my mouth, but my coughing feet startled her awake. She'd never seen such a handsome man before. Immediately, she demanded I'd be her boyfriend. I tried to refuse until I spotted diamonds growing in her armpits. This was next level wealth. I rushed over to pluck them, but she yanked me straight into a trash shoot. I nearly pissed myself in terror. Even the nearby rats were stunned. The next day, I finally escaped, only to discover I turned completely gold. Holy hell, that trash shoe was worth it. All my suffering vanished in an instant. I was rich. Who knew I'd become so valuable I was ready to sell myself on the spot. Then a beam of sunlight hit and me, my body erupted in blinding golden light. A nearby homeless man saw it blunch at me in excitement, and his body started glowing gold, too. The homeless woman finally emerged, but to my shock, she was completely back to normal. Suddenly, I understood. Physical contact passes on the curse. Without hesitation, I grabbed his hand. Let's see how he likes being the golden goose now.

My family only cares about my money, he whispered. If they do anything suspicious, tell me immediately. I had no idea what he meant. But a week later, Grandpa announced he was sick. Terminal. The doctors gave him maybe six months to live. Then suddenly, his family started being nice to me. My husband's mom even hugged me, and his sister complimented my clothes. Something was up. Two weeks after his announcement, I overheard something. I was getting water in the kitchen when I heard my husband's mom talking to him. $200,000 if you divorce her before your grandfather dies, she said. Think about what you could do with that money. My hands started shaking. Were they really bribing my husband to leave me? That night, I reported what I heard to Grandpa. He listened quietly, then said something strange. Perfect. Don't tell him, you know. Let them continue. What was he planning? Why did he sound almost happy? Over the next few weeks, my husband became a different person. Late nights at work, cold shoulders, forgotten anniversaries, I wanted to confront him, but Grandpa told me to stay quiet. So I watched and waited, my stomach in knots every single day. Then I found the proof. While my husband showered, I checked his laptop. There was a bank transfer for exactly $200,000. And a folder labeled Divorce Papers with documents already filled out. He was actually going to leave me for the money. The next day, I met Grandpa at the park. But something was off. He walked fine, talked clearly and didn't cough once. Grandpa, are you actually sick? I asked. He's smiled a little, but not as sick as they think. We needed them to believe I'm dying soon, so they'd rush their plan and make mistakes. This guy was playing everybody. This whole thing was a setup. Document everything he told me. Every text, every phone call, every dollar. So I became a spy in my own marriage. I took screenshots of bank accounts. I recorded his mom's phone calls. I found their family group chat on his laptop, where they discussed the whole scheme.

voice_to_text: My friend called me crying. She saw my husband at a prenatal checkup with another woman. I laughed it off at first because Daniel had texted me an hour earlier saying he was stuck in back to back meetings all afternoon. But Sarah kept insisting she wasn't wrong and I could hear real panic in her voice. I told her she was mistaken, hung up and immediately called Daniel's office. Assistant Jenny answered. And when I asked for him, she said, oh, he took a personal day today. Didn't he tell you? My hand went to my stomach where our baby was growing 16 weeks along. I didn't even change out of my paint stained clothes from working on the nursery. Just grabbed my keys and drove to Grove Medical Center. The receptionist looked uncomfortable when I described Daniel, but she pointed me toward exam room 4 at the end of the hall. I sat down in a chair directly across from the door, pulled out my phone and waited. 30 minutes passed and I, I was starting to think Sarah really had been wrong. Then the door opened and Daniel walked out with his hand on a young blonde woman's back, the same way he always guided me through crowds. I hit record on my phone. She was crying softly and he pulled her into a hug right there in the hallway. We'll figure this out, he said loud enough for my phone to catch every word, I promise. Live, we'll figure this out together. Then his hand moved to her stomach, finger there with the exact same tenderness he'd shown me when we first found out I was pregnant. She wasn't showing yet, but the way he touched her made me want to throw up. I kept recording. As they walk to the reception desk, he pulled out his credit card to pay for her appointment, the same card linked to our joint account that I'd use that morning to buy nursery paint. He wrote down her next appointment date in his leather planner, the same planner where he kept track of my doctor's visits. Only when they turned to leave did he finally see me sitting there. All the color drained from his face in an instant. Emma, he said so quietly, I almost didn't hear it. The blonde followed his gaze and her eyes went wide when she saw my stain shirt and my pregnant belly. I stood up, pocketed my phone and walked out without saying a single word. I hired a tutor who tested him and said his reading level was actually two grades ahead of where he should be. The tutor was completely confused about why he was failing. voice_to_text: What made you quit your night shift job on the spot? I took the night security job at Riverside Medical Archive because it paid $18 an hour and nobody asked questions about my gap here. The building was a converted warehouse on the industrial side of town where the hospital stored old patient records, outdated equipment and files that needed to be kept for legal reasons but nobody ever looked at. My shift ran from eleven PM to seven, 10:00am Thursday through Monday. And for the first two weeks, it was the easiest money I'd ever made. The building had three floors, each one about 40,000 square feet of filing cabinets, storage boxes and the occasional piece of abandoned medical equipment covered in dust. My supervisor, Leonard, was a retired hospital administrator who did the day shift and left me detailed notes about my rounds. Check all entry points at midnight, 2:00am and 5:00am, walk each floor once per shift. Log anything unusual in the notebook at the front desk. Most nights unusual meant a mouse or a flickering light. Everything changed on my third Thursday. I arrived at ten forty five PM like always, and Leonard was waiting by the front desk with an expression I hadn't seen before, something between concern and embarrassment. He handed me the shift log and I noticed his handwriting was shakier than usual. Had something weird happened today? Around four PM, he said, not quite meeting my eyes, got a call from the Third floor landline, you know, the red phone by the old records room. I nodded. I'd seen that phone during my rounds, an ancient rotary model mounted on the wall that I'd assumed didn't work anymore. Thing is, there's nobody up there during the day. Building was locked. I checked the logs. Nobody else has keys except us and the main hospital security, and they didn't send anyone. He paused, looking uncomfortable when I answered. There was just breathing, heavy breathing, like someone had been running. Then they hung up. I felt something cold settle in my stomach. Did you check the third floor? Leonard nodded quickly watched the whole thing. Nothing. No signs of entry. Nothing. Probably just a phone malfunction, old wiring causing a phantom call or something. After Leonard left, I sat at the front desk trying to convince myself it was nothing. Old buildings had weird electrical issues all the time. But the image of that red phone kept pushing into my thoughts. Midnight, I started my first round, taking the stairs to the third floor with my flashlight, even though the overhead fluorescent were working fine. The third floor was a maze of filing cabinets arranged in rows like library sacks, creating dozens of narrow aisles that stretched back into shadow. I walked the perimeter, first checking each of the four fire exits, all locked.

voice_to_text: My parents said they were too tired to come to my graduation, but they posted photos at my sister's spa day. I didn't say anything until my name was called for valedictorian. I looked into the camera and said to everyone who didn't show up, this one's for you. Two hours later, my sister was crying in the parking lot. Three days before graduation, my father called. Dora, your mother and I are too tired to make the trip. We've had a very busy month. Too tired. I'm valedictorian. I'm giving the speech. We're very proud, he said, though his tone said otherwise. He hung up before I could protest. I sat in my dorm, phone in hand. The highest achievement of my life and they couldn't drive two hours. My roommate Jesse found me an hour later, tear stained. They're not coming. The next morning I checked social media. Then I saw it. My sister Abby's Instagram story. Her smiling face flanked by our parents all holding champagne. Caption, family spa day. So needed this. I swiped through massages, facials, lunch. One photo showed mom and Abby in matching robes. Caption, mother daughter goals. Mom's comment, best day with my baby girl. They weren't tired. They were pampering my sister. I texted Abby, saw your spa day posts. Interesting timing. Her reply, don't make it a big deal. Not everything is about you and your school stuff. School stuff. My valedictorian graduation reduced to school stuff. I opened my Graduation speech, words about resilience and finding your voice felt hollow. I created a new document. Words poured out fueled by a lifetime of being second place. Graduation morning, I stood at the podium with both versions in front of me. I looked out at supportive friends, proud families and three empty seats where my parents should have been. I pushed the original speech aside. All my life, I've wanted to be noticed, to feel like I matter. Today, that changes. The audience grew quiet. I spent years believing if I just achieved more, I would finally be seen, that the people who should love me would acknowledge my worth. I glanced at the live stream camera. Today I see empty seats where my family should be. They told me they were too tired. Though social media reveals they found energy for other celebrations this weekend, a murmur ran through the crowd. Their absence taught me I am enough, with or without their validation.

voice_to_text: Lulu was completely still beside me. Her mouth was closed. She was silent, facing the back of the van. The panting wasn't her. It was coming from behind us, from the back of the van. My hands shook as Lulu showed her teeth and growled. I fumbled with the door and practically fell out. Lulu jumped after me, keeping herself between me and the van. I heard the metallic click of the back door unlocking from inside. It swung open and a body tumbled out. Dean, wearing only underwear, dripping with sweat, holding a hunting knife. Finally, he got three hours of the stupid Mut barking. Every time I tried to make my move, she'd go crazy. My brain couldn't process it. He'd been hiding in my van for hours, waiting. You should be thanking me, Dean said, tossing the knife between his hands. Way out of your league. Truth is, it wasn't even my idea. My brother Abel thought you looked perfect. So I said, sure, I'll grab you and bring you back. That's what good brothers do. I wanted his first time to be special. Abel, quiet. Abel, who loaded my van. They planned this together. Would have been easy if not for your stupid dog. He gripped the knife, crouching toward Lulu. But now I'm fixing that problem. He lunged forward, the blade slashing across Lulu's back. Blood poured as she yelled. But then Dean screamed. Lulu had bitten through his hand. She took my hand. Blood. Spurted from his wrist as he grabbed the knife with his other hand. I'm going to kill her. But Lulu was already airborne, launching herself despite the blood streaming from her back. This time she went for his throat. Police arrived to find Dean unconscious, face shredded, barely alive. His DNA matched all seven murdered women. For a year and a half, the brothers had been sabotaging cars on that highway. When young women traveled alone, they'd use the tow truck to take them to. They'd started killing right after their mother died. The same mother Richard said passed peacefully in her sleep. But here's what haunts me. Lulu knew from the moment Dean touched my van. She knew those three hours of non stop barking weren't random. She, I could smell him hiding back there, desperately trying to warn me while he waited in the dark with his knife. The news called Lulu a hero. That night I patted my bed. You sleep up here from now on, girl. She hopped up carefully, still sore, and curled against my legs. Sometimes I still think about Abel's whisper, drive safe. He knew his brother was hidden in my van. He knew what was supposed to happen to me in those woods. If it wasn't for an ugly dog nobody wanted, I would have been No. 8.

Lee lost it, started breaking down the door with his rifle butt. He got halfway through before he dropped, assuming the same position as Jensen, kneeling, covering his eyes. That's when I saw it through the holes in the door. A massive insect like appendage covered in violence.

Seven women found dead in the woods beyond the cornfields, all in the past year and a half, all young women traveling alone. When the van was ready, Dean was gone. Will handed me the keys, stared at me a second too long, then whispered, Drive safe. Something about how he said it made my skin crawl. The highway that night was horror movie dark. I kept feeling like eyes were watching from the cornfields. The moment we passed into the forest, Lulu exploded. voice_to_text: My fiance demands I remove my son from our wedding party because he's proof I loved another woman first. Rachel and I had been together for two years when she dropped this bomb three weeks before our wedding. My son Tommy is 7. His mother died in childbirth. I raised him alone from day one. No family help, no support system. Me and this tiny human who needed everything from me. Those first years were brutal. I worked nights at a warehouse while Tommy stayed with a retired neighbor, then rushed home at 6:00am to get him ready for daycare before my day job at an accounting firm. I survived on three hours of sleep for years, but we made it work. Tommy grew into this amazing kid. Smart, funny, and kind to everyone he meets. When I met Rachel at a company mixer, she seemed perfect. She laughed at Tommy's Dinosaur jokes, helped with his homework, and came to his soccer games. Tommy started calling her Miss Rachel, then just Rachel. And recently, he'd asked if he could call her mom. After the wedding, I thought I'd found someone who loved us both. We built a life together. Rachel moved into our house last year. She redecorated Tommy's room with him getting out rocket ship wallpaper he'd been begging for. She packed his lunches with little notes. She even started a college fund for him, putting in $200 every month. Or so I thought. Three weeks ago, Rachel sat Me down after Tommy went to bed. She needed to discuss the wedding. Great. I figured we'd talk about flowers or the playlist instead. She said Tommy couldn't be the ring bearer. When I asked why, she said she'd been thinking about it for months. Every time she looked at him, she saw my dead wife. He was living proof that I'd loved someone else first, that she'd always be second place. She wanted our wedding to be about us, not about my past. I told her that was insane. Tommy was my son, not some symbol. She said I didn't understand how hard it was for her, always competing with a ghost. She said something that made my blood run cold. Once we have our own kids, we should consider sending Tommy to boarding school. He'd get a better education, and we could focus on our real family.

She reached for the phone, but I pulled it back. Those are from the shoebox in your closet, I said, the one behind the winter coat. What conferences. Bryce hadn't said a word. He just kept scroll going through the photos with this blank expression that broke my heart. Finally, he looked up at her. His voice was completely calm. voice_to_text: I can't keep my brother's wife's dirty secret anymore. My brother Bryce married Romie three years ago. And at first I thought she was exactly what he needed. Bryce is a nurse and works brutal 12 hour night shifts at the hospital. He'd come home exhausted and Romie would have dinner ready, the house clean. She played the perfect wife role flawlessly, maybe too flawlessly. About six months ago, I started noticing small things. During family dinner, she'd excuse herself to take phone calls that apparently couldn't wait. She'd come back smiling, but her hands would be shaking slightly. Then I saw the second phone, just a glimpse when her purse fell open at Thanksgiving. She grabbed it quickly and made some excuse. It's about it being a work on. Romie's a freelance graphic designer who works from home. Why would she need two phones? I told myself I was being paranoid. Bryce seemed happy. Who was I to start digging into his marriage over gut feelings? But the calls kept happening. The mysterious appointments she'd mentioned vaguely, the new clothes and perfume that seemed too, too nice for someone working from their home office. Two months ago they asked me to help move furniture for their home office renovation. Bryce was at work, so it was just me and Romie while she was Distracted on a call, I opened their bedroom closet looking for that dolly Bryce mentioned. That's when I saw it, a shoebox tucked behind winter coats. Something made me look inside. Hotel receipts, at least 20 of them, all from the Marriott downtown, all from the past six months, all on weeknights when Bryce worked his hospital shifts. My hands were shaking as I took photos of every single one before putting the box back. Exactly how I found it. I spent the next two weeks in agony. Do I tell Bryce and destroy his marriage over suspicions? What if there's an explanation? But deep down, I knew the evidence was damning. The dates matched play with her mysterious appointments. Then three weeks ago, Bryce called me at 2:00am sobbing. Romie had just told him she wanted a divorce, said she'd fallen out of love, that the spark was gone. He was absolutely.

voice_to_text: And when he spoke again, there was something almost amused in his tone. Well, I suppose physically I'm quite stiff, which is to be expected given the circumstances. I felt my stomach turn over because the details were too specific to matter of fact to be a prank. Pranksters usually go for shock value or try to get a reaction. They don't provide mundane details about pet feeding schedules and furniture positioning. Pulled up the address database and typed in 1847 Rosewood Lane, which immediately populated with resident information. Harold Finch, age 73, widower. No emergency contacts listed. No previous 9 1 1 calls from this address in the system history. Mr. Finch, I'm sending police and emergency medical services to your address right now. I need you to stay on the line with me until they arrive. I'd already flagged the call for immediate dispatch. Sending units to the address with a note about possible mental health crisis. But my screen showed an error message I've never seen before. Location verification failed. Unable to route emergency services. I stared at the message, trying to understand what it meant, because in 10 years of dispatching I'd never seen the system simply refused to send help. Harold's voice came back through my headset, still patient, still apologetic. Oh, I'm afraid I can't stay on the line much longer, dear. There are others waiting to call, and it wouldn't be fair to monopolize your time. But I did want to make sure someone knew about my body. My daughter lives in California, and I hate for her to fly back and find me like this. Air key is under the ceramic frog by the front door, if that helps your officers get inside. Thank you so much for your assistance. Then the line went dead. Just clicked off, and my screen showed the call had lasted exactly 3 minutes and 17 seconds. I sat there staring at my console, trying to process what had just happened. The rational part of my brain said this was a prank or confused elderly man who wasn't actually dead. But something deeper and more instinctive was screaming that I just experienced something fundamentally wrong. I manually entered the address into the dispatch system by passing the automatic routing and sent a welfare check request with high priority. 2 patrol units acknowledged and confirmed they were on route. Estimated arrival in 8 minutes. I logged the call details and flagged it for supervisor review, typing out a summary that sounded insane. Caller reported his own death, provided specific details. Call terminated before EMS could be routed. Request immediate welfare check. My supervisor Linda Kovatch appeared behind my station within two minutes, reading over my shoulder, you wrote that a dead man called 9 1 1. Her tone wasn't accusatory, just used, and I explained as best I could about the call's content and the strange system error that had prevented normal routing. Linda had been supervising dispatch for 20 years, and she'd seen everything, but she looked genuinely puzzled by this one. Pull up the call recording, she said, leaning closer to my screen. Let's hear exactly what this guy said. And that's when things took a turn I never expected. Full story is linked below or on my channel.

I found the file on his laptop during Thanksgiving when he asked me to print directions. Excel tabs stretched across the screen, each one named for a different female relative. My cousin Rebecca, Aunt Patricia, my sister Natalie, me. The first sheet dated back eight years. Detailed logs of estimated ovulation dates, lengths, fertility predictions. But then I scrolled right. Compatibility scores, IQ estimates, physical trait rankings, charts mapping out theoretical offspring between specific family members. Rebecca plus cousin David equals 91% genetic optimisation. The spreadsheet assigned numerical values to eye colour, hair texture, bone structure. My hands shook as I hit print on the directions, then sent the whole file to my email before closing the laptop. Thanksgiving dinner that night felt different, knowing what I'd seen. Uncle Michael sat at the head of the table like always, leading prayer and carving Turkey. But I watched him, watching the women. How his eyes tracked my sister as she served potatoes. The way he smiled when Aunt Patricia mentioned Rebecca wasn't feeling well, asking pointed questions about symptoms. Rebecca is sixteen. My stomach turned. I caught my mom's eye across the table, and she frowned, sensing something wrong. I couldn't explain it. There, with 23 family members crowded around Uncle Michael's Wife Diane, beaming at her husband's generosity hosting everyone. My phone buzzed under the table and email from Michael underscore Hoffman two eight, one at Gmail dot com with the subject line File Access Notification. The body text was simple I know you opened the project folder. We should talk after dessert. Alone. My throat closed up. I looked at Uncle Michael, and he was staring directly at me. His fork paused halfway to his mouth. He smiled. Small, controlled, terrifying. Then he winked and resumed eating, asking my dad about his golf game like nothing happened. I told mom I felt sick and needed to leave immediately. She protested because we hadn't even had pie yet, but something in my face made her stop mid sentence. We were in the car within 10 minutes. My sister Natalie, confused but following mom, drove in silence for three blocks before pulling into a grocery store parking lot and demanding to know what happened. I showed her the email. Then I forwarded her my copy of the spreadsheet and watched her face change as she scrolled through it.

voice_to_text: I've been a 9 1 1 dispatcher for 10 years. Last night I got a call which made me quit forever. The call came in at 2:00am on a Thursday, which should have been my first warning, because nothing good ever happens at 2:00am. I've been working the overnight shift at the county emergency dispatch center for a decade, and I developed an instinct for calls that would ruin your night versus calls that would ruin your life. This one felt different the moment the line connected, not because of what was said, but because of what I heard in the background. Silence. Complete, absolute silence. No ambient noise, no breathing, no static. Just a void that felt like it was pulling sound into itself rather than transmitting it. Then a voice, elderly and male, with the kind of gentle politeness that reminded me of my grandfather. Hello, dear. I'm terribly sorry to bother you at this hour, but I need to report that I've died. Could you send someone to collect my body? I'm at 1847 Rosewood Lane, and I'm afraid I'm making quite a mess on the carpet. The words were so matter of fact delivered with such apologetic courtesy that my brain took a full three seconds to process what he'd actually said. I'm trained for panic, for confusion, for people who can barely speak through their terror. I'm not trained for someone calmly reporting their own death like they're calling about a missed trash pickup. My First thought was dementia or a confused elderly person having some kind of mental health crisis, which happens more often than people realize. I kept my voice steady and professional, the tone I'd perfected over thousands of calls. Sir, this is 9 1 1 emergency services. Can you tell me your name and describe what's happening? Are you injured? There was a pause, and I could hear what sounded like a gentle. My name was Harold Finch, dear. And no, I'm not having trouble breathing because I'm not breathing at all anymore. I had a heart attack approximately 40 minutes ago while watching the evening news, and I've been sitting here in my armchair ever since. I know you're terribly busy, but someone really should come collect me before I start to smell. The way he said it, so practical and considerate, made my skin crawl in a way I couldn't articulate. I glanced at my screen, checking the call origin data that usually populated automatically. But the location field was blank, just showing unknown where the address should have been. I tried a different approach, thinking maybe this was an elaborate prank. Mister Finch, I need you to tell me if you're experiencing any pain or discomfort right now. Another pause, longer this time.

We received information about potential physical abuse, one said, reading from Clipboard. Ethan stood in the doorway behind them, looking almost proud. The bathroom faucet dripped constantly, and the landlord kept saying he'd fix it, but never did. I put a bowl under it to catch the water because I couldn't afford the Bill going up. He pulled out this tiny red screwdriver that squeaked when you pressed it. Then I'm gonna fix everything, he said. And he just started walking around our apartment fixing stuff. My sketchbooks were shoved in with dirty laundry. He stopped at a gas station halfway there, filled up, didn't offer to buy me anything. When we pulled into her driveway, he popped the trunk and said, I had a week to pick a real major or figure something else out. Grandma opened the door in her yellow apron. She looked at the bags, then at him, then at me, didn't ask questions, just took one bag and told me to grab the other. He left before I made it up the porch steps. She had early stage Parkinson's. Her hands shook when she poured coffee, when she helped me unpack, when she handed me the key to her garage and set. I could use it however I needed. That garage became my studio. She'd sit on this old folding chair watching me work, hands folded in her lap to hide the tremors. I was 17 when she started falling. My sister Violet's three kids are well behaved because they sit on phones silently. Tommy asks questions about grandfather clocks and how things work, which apparently makes him difficult. voice_to_text: I told my daughter in law she is not a mother. So I have three kids and they're all married now. Mother's Day rolled around and honestly, everyone was super busy with their own stuff. Nobody could come visit me, which was fine. I get it. So I decided to put together some nice baskets for my daughter and my pregnant daughter in law. Just some candles, chocolates, a cute mug, that kind of thing. Nothing crazy expensive but thoughtful. Now, here's the thing about Jenny. She has two golden retrievers named biscuit and Moose and she's always making these comments about how they're my first grandkids. Like every family dinner she'd bring it up. I honestly just thought she was joking around because of the whole infertility situation. Never took it seriously. My daughter posted a photo in our family group chat showing off everything she got for Mother's Day, including my basket. My pregnant daughter in law also sent a thank you message for hers. Normal stuff. Then my phone rang. It was Jenny. She asked where her basket was. I was genuinely confused and asked what she meant. For a second I thought maybe she was telling me she was pregnant and this was her way of announcing it. My heart actually Jumped a little, but no. She said since I already have two grandkids by her, she should have gotten a basket, too. Then she said biscuit and Moose's names. I just stood there in my kitchen holding the phone thinking I heard her wrong. So I asked her to repeat that. She said it again. She's the mother of her dog so she deserved a Mother's Day basket just like my other daughter's in law. I'll be honest, I laughed, not to be mean, but because I thought she was messing with me. But she wasn't laughing back. That's when I told her she's not a mother. I said Mother's Day is for women who raise actual human children, not for pet owners. I didn't say it mean or anything, just stated it like a fact. She completely lost it on me, started yelling about how dare I invalidate her and that she is a parent and her dogs are her babies. She said I was cruel and heartless and that I clearly don't care about her struggles with infertility. Then she hung up on me. I texted my son after to explain what happened and he called me back pissed, said I was way out of line and that I need to apologize to Jenny and send her a basket immediately. I told him I'm not doing that because it's ridiculous. Dogs are not children. I have nothing against her dogs, but come on, he said, I'm being insensitive. To her pain and that she considers herself a dog mom, so I should respect that. I said, fine, she can call herself whatever she wants, but that doesn't mean I have to buy into it and send her Mother's Day gifts for her pets. Now my son isn't talking to me. Jenny blocked me on everything.

voice_to_text: I've been a 9 1 1 dispatcher for 10 years. Last night I got a call which made me quit forever. The call came in at 2:00am on a Thursday, which should have been my first warning because nothing good ever happens at 2:00am. I've been working the overnight shift at the county emergency dispatch center for a decade and I developed an instinct for calls that would ruin your night versus calls that would ruin your life. This one felt different the moment the line connected, not because of what was said, but because of what I heard in the background. Silence, absolute silence. No ambient noise, no breathing, no static, just a void that felt like it was pulling sound into itself rather than transmitting it. Then a voice, elderly and male, with the kind of gentle politeness that reminded me of my grandfather. Hello, dear. I'm terribly sorry to bother you at this hour, but I need to report that I've died. Could you send someone to collect my body? I'm at 1847 Rosewood Lane and I'm afraid I'm making quite a mess on the carpet. The words were so matter of fact, delivered with such apologetic courtesy that my brain took a full three seconds to process what he'd actually said. I'm trained for panic fusion for people who can barely speak through their terror. I'm not trained for someone calmly reporting their own death like they're calling about a missed trash pickup. My first thought, Was dementia or a confused elderly person having some kind of mental health crisis, which happens more often than people realize. I kept my voice steady and professional, the tone I perfected over thousands of calls. Sir, this is 9 1 1 emergency services. Can you tell me your name and describe what's happening? Are you injured? There was a pause and I could hear what sounded like a gentle sigh. My name is Harold Finch, dear. And no, I'm not having trouble breathing because I'm not breathing at all anymore. I had a heart attack approximately 40 minutes ago while watching the evening news, and I've been sitting here in my armchair ever since. I know you're terribly busy, but someone really should come collect me before I start to smell. The way he said it, so practical and considerate, made my skin crawl in a way I couldn't articulate. I glanced at my screen, checking the call origin data that usually populated automatically. But the location field was blank, just showing unknown where the address should have been. I tried a different approach, thinking maybe this was an elaborate prank. Mister Finch, I need you to tell me if you're experiencing any pain or discomfort right now. Another pause, longer this time. And when he spoke again, there was something almost amused in his tone. Well, I suppose physically I'm quite stiff, which is to be expected given the circumstances. My left arm is still clutching the remote. Control, though I can't seem to let go of it now. There's a rather unpleasant smell starting to develop and I believe my cat whiskers has been nibbling on my ankle, though I can't blame her since I forgot to fill her food bowl before I died. I felt my stomach turn over because the details were too specific, matter of fact, to be a prank. Pranksters usually go for shock value or try to get a reaction. They don't provide mundane details about pet feeding schedules and furniture positioning. I pulled up the address database and typed in 1847 Rosewood Lane, which immediately populated with resident information. Harold Finch, age 73, widower. No emergency contacts listed. No previous 9 1 1 calls from this address in the system history. Mr Finch, I'm sending police and.

And soon I begin to slide. Panic. I quickly come up with an idea, spreading my legs wide, pressing my head to the ground for more friction, barely managing to stop myself.
